  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Military Encampment
  author: Lee Kyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Red banners flutter and wave in the wind, filling half the sky,
    Blue pavilions eclipse the sun, standing tall upon the mountain peak.
    The drums of three armies thunder through the air like roaring lightning,
    Smoke from ten thousand cookfires gathers above like clouds crowning the ridge.

    Though my brush traces war proclamations, I blush at my own dullness,
    Yet the strategies within this command tent rely upon your wisdom.
    When at last we bind the chieftain's hands and lead him captive away,
    We shall sing songs of victory along the willow-lined road of return.
  footnotes:
    - The 'three armies' refers to the traditional division of military forces in East Asian warfare.
    - The image of willows lining the homeward path is a classical symbol of triumph and return in Chinese and Korean poetry.
    - Lee Kyubo (1168-1241) was a renowned Goryeo-era scholar-official and poet, often praised for his mastery of Chinese poetic forms.
